{
  "doc_id": "14459",
  "text": "One concern with this method is that it is hard to evaluate the extent to which replication fork inhibitors obscure the relative efficiencies or normal firing time of origins [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Nonetheless, this has become a routine assay in yeasts that has been used to assess the effects of specific mutations on the firing of origins throughout the genome [CITATION_5] . However, it has not been exploited at genome scale in mammalian cells, partly owing to the complexity of the genome. A variation of this method has been used to map origins on an array covering 120 kb of the Chinese hamster dihydrofolate reductase locus in a cell line harbouring 1,000 amplified copies of the locus [CITATION_6] , but this is clearly an underexplored methodology for identifying mammalian origins.",
